#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:3
msgid "Rust specific directives"
msgstr "Rust 專屬的指示詞"

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:7
msgid ""
"Understanding this is not required to use the tool. Most things can be "
"achieved with :doc:`including` and :doc:`roles`. This is an internal "
"interface and there is no guarantee of stability."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:10
msgid ""
"The extension adds the directives listed here, that are used by the :rust:"
"exe:`sphinx-rustdocgen` in its output. All directives, except :rst:dir:`rust:"
"use`, can have content. Directives can be nested under each other for "
"structuring the documentation. See the documentation for the individual "
"directives, if defining them manually in a document. However, that is not a "
"recommended use and the directives are designed for programmatic creation "
"and manipulation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:15
msgid "All directives, except :rst:dir:`rust:use`, take the following options:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:0
msgid "index"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:17
msgid ""
"(Required) A integer that indicates the type of the index. See :py:class:"
"`sphinxcontrib_rust.items.SphinxIndexEntryType` or :rust:enum:"
"`sphinx_rustdocgen::directives::IndexEntryType` for values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:0
msgid "vis"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:20
msgid ""
"(Required) The visibility of the directive, ``pub``, ``crate`` or ``pvt``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:0
msgid "layout"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:21
msgid ""
"(Optional) A JSON list of :py:class:`sphinxcontrib_rust.nodes.Node` objects. "
"Currently, the JSON must be entirely on one line. If not provided, the "
"directives signature will be rendered as the item type in a keyword node and "
"the last segment of the directive item's path as the name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:0
msgid "toc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:25
msgid ""
"(Optional) The signature of the directive to display in the ``toctree``. By "
"default, this is the item type and the identifier of the item."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:30
msgid ""
"The ``.. rust:crate:: <crate_name>`` directive documents the crate itself, "
"using the documentation from the ``lib.rs`` file. ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:33
msgid ""
".. rust:crate:: <my_crate>\n"
"\n"
"   This is my awesome crate.\n"
"\n"
"   .. rust:module:: <my_crate>::<some_module>\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:42
msgid ""
"The ``.. rust:enum:: <enum_path>`` directive documents an enum. To document "
"individual variants, use the ``struct`` directive and nest it under the "
"``enum`` directive. ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:45
msgid ""
".. rust:enum:: <my_crate>::<some_module>::<my_enum>\n"
"\n"
"   Enum docstring here\n"
"\n"
"   .. rust:struct:: <my_crate>::<some_module>::<my_enum>::<variant0>\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:54
msgid ""
"The ``.. rust:executable:: <executable_name>`` directive documents an "
"executable provided by the crate. Note that the target here is the name of "
"the generated executable, and not a Rust path to the executable. Items "
"within the executable can be referenced with the executable name as the "
"prefix instead of the crate name. ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:58
msgid ""
".. rust:executable:: <my-crate>\n"
"\n"
"   This is my awesome crate's executable.\n"
"\n"
"   .. rust:module:: <my-crate>::<some_module>\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:67
msgid ""
"The ``.. rust:function:: <fn_path>`` directive documents a function. The "
"function may be an associated function of a struct/enum, or part of a trait "
"impl of a struct."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:70
msgid ""
"In such cases, the path to the function is ``<module_path>::<struct_ident>::"
"<fn_ident>`` or ``<module_path>::<struct_ident>::<trait_ident>::"
"<fn_ident>``. The ``module_path`` must be the path of the module in which "
"the struct or the enum is defined, and not where the impl is defined."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:74
msgid ""
"The directive can also be used for a function declaration within an ``extern "
"\"C\"`` block. In this case, the function is nested directly under the "
"module and the reference path should be ``<module_path>::<fn_ident>``. ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:77
msgid ""
".. rust::module:: <my_crate>::<some_module>\n"
"   .. rust:function:: <my_crate>::<some_module>::<func>\n"
"\n"
"      Function docstring here.\n"
"\n"
".. rust:struct:: <my_crate>::<some_module>::<struct>\n"
"   .. rust:impl:: <my_crate>::<some_module>::<struct>\n"
"      .. rust:function:: <my_crate>::<some_module>::<struct>::<func>\n"
"\n"
"         Function docstring here\n"
"\n"
"   .. rust:impl:: <my_crate>::<some_module>::<struct>::<trait>\n"
"      .. rust:function:: <my_crate>::<some_module>::<struct>::<trait>::"
"<trait_func>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:93
msgid ""
"The ``.. rust:impl:: <impl_path>`` directive documents an impl block. For "
"inherent impl blocks, the path is the path to the ``Self`` type of the impl "
"block (i.e. the struct or enum). For trait impl blocks, the path is the path "
"to the ``Self`` type, followed by the trait name. This also applies to trait "
"impls on generics, where the ``Self`` type is the generic used (``T``, "
"``Vec<T>``, etc.)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:98
msgid ""
"If manually writing the documentation, it is best to nest impl blocks under "
"the struct/enum's directive, with the impl block of the struct/enum first, "
"followed by various trait impls of the struct/enum."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:103
msgid "The ``.. rust:macro:: <marco_path>`` directive documents a macro. ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:105
msgid ""
".. rust:module:: <my_crate>::<some_module>\n"
"   .. rust:macro:: <my_crate>::<some_module>::<macro>\n"
"\n"
"      Macro docstring."
msgstr ""
".. rust:module:: <my_crate>::<some_module>\n"
"   .. rust:macro:: <my_crate>::<some_module>::<macro>\n"
"\n"
"      Macro docstring."

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:112
msgid ""
"The ``.. rust:module:: <module_path>`` directive documents a macro. When the "
"module contains other modules, they can be nested under the parent module's "
"directive or in a different file and linked to parent module using a "
"``toctree``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:115
msgid ""
"The :doc:`sphinx-rustdocgen` automatically organizes the module directives "
"based on where the module's items are defined and places the links in the "
"parent module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:120
msgid ""
"The ``.. rust:struct:: <struct_path>`` directive documents a struct, a union "
"or an enum variant. When documenting an enum variant, the path is ``.. rust:"
"struct::<enum_path>::<variant>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:123
msgid ""
"To document individual fields, use the :rst:dir:`rust:variable` directive "
"and nest it under the struct directive. ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:125
msgid ""
".. rust:module:: <my_crate>::<some_module>\n"
"   .. rust:struct:: <my_crate>::<some_module>::<struct>\n"
"\n"
"      Struct's docstring.\n"
"\n"
"      .. rust:variable:: <my_crate>::<some_module>::<struct>::<field0>\n"
"\n"
"         Field's docstring."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:136
msgid "The ``.. rust:trait:: <trait_path>`` directive documents a trait. ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:138
msgid ""
".. rust:module:: <my_crate>::<some_module>\n"
"   .. rust:trait:: <my_crate>::<some_module>::<trait>\n"
"\n"
"      Trait's docstring.\n"
"\n"
"      .. rust:type:: <my_crate>::<some_module>::<trait>::<assoc_type>\n"
"\n"
"         Type's docstring.\n"
"\n"
"      .. rust:function:: <my_crate>::<some_module>::<trait>::"
"<trait_function>\n"
"\n"
"         Function's docstring."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:153
msgid ""
"The ``.. rust:type:: <type_path>`` directive documents a type defined with "
"``type T = ...`` syntax, including types within a trait or an extern block."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:158
msgid ""
"The ``.. rust:use::`` directive is a meta-directive that has no content. The "
"argument to the directive is a path that is used in the file being processed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:161
msgid ""
"The directive has a required option, ``used_name``, which indicates the name "
"provided by the use path that can be used in references in the same file. "
"The value can be set to ``self`` to reference items defined within the "
"document itself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:165
msgid ""
"It also has an optional option, ``reexport``, whose value is the path under "
"which the name is reexported. This is generally the path of the module in "
"which the use statement appears."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:168
msgid ""
"This allows using shorter paths for Rust item references within the document "
"itself. Note that this only applies to references, and not directive names."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:171
msgid ""
"There can be multiple ``rust:use`` directives in a document. If there are "
"conflicts, the last defined mapping is picked. ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:174
msgid ""
".. rust:module:: <my_crate>::<some_module>\n"
"\n"
"   .. rust:use:: <my_crate>::<other_module>::<other_struct>\n"
"      :used_name: <other_struct>\n"
"\n"
"   .. rust:use:: <my_crate>::<some_module>::<submodule>::<submodule_struct>\n"
"      :used_name: <submodule_struct>\n"
"      :reexport: <my_crate>::<some_module>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:185
msgid ""
"The ``.. rust:variable:: <variable_path>`` directive documents a variable or "
"a field in a struct."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:187
msgid ""
"For fields, the path is the ``<struct_path>::<field_name>``. For tuple "
"structs, the ``field_name`` is the index of the field within the tuple."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/directives.rst:190
msgid ""
"The variable can also be a static variable declaration within an ``extern "
"\"C\"`` block. In this case, the variable is nested directly under the "
"module and the reference path should be ``<module_path>::<type_ident>``."
msgstr ""
